A Round-Robin Arbiter is an arbitration logic that rotates priority among requesters. 
So that every requester gets a fair chance to access a shared resource.

ğŸ“Œ Definition
In a round-robin arbiter:
Priority is dynamic, not fixed
After a requester is granted, it goes to lowest priority
Next arbitration starts from the next requester
Prevents starvation

Example:
Priority: req[0] > req[1] > req[2] > req[3]
Assume the last granted = req[1]
req[2] â†’ req[3] â†’ req[0] â†’ req[1]
If requests are:
req = 4'b1011   // req[3], req[1], req[0] active
Grant will be:
grant = 4'b0001  // req[0] gets grant (next after req[1])

ğŸ” Round-Robin Arbiter Example (4 Requesters)
Assume:
Requesters: req[0] req[1] req[2] req[3]
Initial last_grant = 0
Arbitration checks start after last_grant

ğŸ“Š Cycle-by-Cycle Table
| Cycle | last_grant (start) | req[3:0] | Priority Order Checked | Grant         | last_grant (end) |
| ----- | ------------------ | -------- | ---------------------- | ------------- | ---------------- |
| 0     | 0                  | 1111     | 1 â†’ 2 â†’ 3 â†’ 0          | 0010 (req[1]) | 1                |
| 1     | 1                  | 1011     | 2 â†’ 3 â†’ 0 â†’ 1          | 1000 (req[3]) | 3                |
| 2     | 3                  | 0101     | 0 â†’ 1 â†’ 2 â†’ 3          | 0001 (req[0]) | 0                |
| 3     | 0                  | 0100     | 1 â†’ 2 â†’ 3 â†’ 0          | 0100 (req[2]) | 2                |



